The Imo state Sector Commander of Federal Road Safety Corps, RS9.4, Roland Onamusi has warned that any transport company that fails to comply with the corona virus pandemic protocol will be blacklisted and suspended. “Any transport company found by our monitoring team that is not COVID-19 pandemic protocols compliant will be blacklisted and suspended from operation”. Onamusi stated this on Wednesday in Owerri, the state capital during the stakeholders meeting with fleet operators and transport unions. He regretted that transport companies were not complying with the COVID protocol, adding that the non-compliance had adversely affected the operations of the FRSC in the state. The Sector Commander however, noted the COVID-19 had affected all transport, entertainment, school and hospitality companies among others and stated that the essence of the meeting was to stop its further negative effect on the global socio-economic life. “Schools, entertainment, transport both air, water and land among others have been negatively by the COVID-19 pandemic. The essence of the meeting is to contain/checkmate the pandemic and its effects”. He warned the transport companies to severely respect the COVID-19 protocol. Speaking on COVID-19 protocols, the Deputy Corps Commander in-charge of Operations, Evaristus Ebeniro mentioned: Physical distancing, Constant use of nose mask, Proper washing of hands, Use of disinfectants, Checking of temperature, Loading of passengers in registered motor parks, Promotion of electronic payment and Non-use of air conditioner on transit among others. On electronic payment, he admonished that payment of transport fares should be done electronically to avoid people from clustering at payment point in transport companies. According to him, “Transport operators should discourage the use of air conditioners in buses or transport vehicles. This will help to provide enough ventilation for passengers to contain the spread of the virus”.